        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>237 S. Desplaines St.<lb/>
            Chicago&#44; Febr. 2. 1877.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. S. Morais<lb/>
            Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>Yesterday I happened to meet Mr. Kunreuther on the street&#44;<lb/> and he told me that&#44; according to a letter from you&#44; Luzzatto&#39;s<lb/> Pentateuch has already been mailed to him.  I am glad that this<lb/> is so.  For now I shall have an opportunity to enjoy myself<lb/> with the reading of the commentary of &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; the great &#91;Hebrew&#93; Mr. K.<lb/> will be kind enough to let me have his copy.<lb/></p>
            <p>I promised you&#44; a few days ago&#44; to substantiate my<lb/> assertion that &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34; is to be dissolved into &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and<lb/> not in &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  I could devote but very little time<lb/> to researches concerning this point&#44; yet I believe that my<lb/> opinion can be proven as correct by the scanty material on<lb/> my hand.<lb/></p>
            <p>The city of Sevilla appears in the Hebrew writings of the middle<lb/> ages under the name of &#91;Hebrew&#93; or &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; so f. i. very often<lb/> in the &#91;Hebrew&#93;; in &#91;Hebrew&#93; p. 131&#44; a &#40;the edition before me<lb/> is sine loco et anno&#41; in a document dated 1354&#44; published<lb/> in &#91;Hebrew&#93; I p. 15&#44; and in numerous other places.<lb/></p>
            <p>As to the name &#34;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#34; &#40;<hi rend="underline">the</hi> Sevillian&#41;&#44; it is formed<lb/> analogously as the surnames &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#40;from Florence&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; &#40;from Lunel&#91;&#63;&#93;&#41; &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#38;c. &#38;c.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>In the &#91;Hebrew&#93; I find the &#91;Hebrew&#93; twice mentioned&#44; viz&#58; page<lb/> 70&#44; a. and 132&#44; a&#59; in both places as &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Mark<lb/> the &#91;Hebrew&#93; in &#91;Hebrew&#93; &#40;the Sevillian&#41;&#44; and remember that<lb/> sometimes we find it construed with the Arabic article<lb/> &#40;&#91;Hebrew&#93;&#41;.  R. Joseph Karo often cites opinions of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; in his &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; as f. i. ad &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> If now Aguilar thinks fit to remark &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> he makes a supposed correction which is &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  The reading of &#91;Hebrew&#93; he has misunder&#45;<lb/>stood.  It is true that Aguilar was a thorough con&#45;<lb/>noisseur of our Hebrew literature&#44; and he is in most<lb/> cases reliable.  Yet he is not free from mistakes.  So&#44; f. i.<lb/> in regard to &#91;Hebrew&#93; he <del>makes</del> repeats the statement of the<lb/> author of &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; that R. Meir Halevi was the teacher of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  But this cannot have been the case&#44; as &#91;Hebrew&#93; died<lb/> already 1244&#44; long before the time of the Sevillian<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; 216 &#91;Hebrew&#93;.  Permit me to add also that Graetz &#40;VIII p. 352&#41;&#44;<lb/> Zunz &#40;Zur Geschichte&#44; p. 379&#41;&#44; Roest &#40;in his catalogue &#91;Hebrew&#93; p. 153&#41;&#44;<lb/> Steinschneider &#40;in &#91;Hebrew&#93; I. p. 116&#41; mention &#91;Hebrew&#93; with adding the<lb/> words&#58; &#34;aus Sevilla.&#34;  So it seems&#44; I do not stand alone<lb/> with my explanation of the term &#91;Hebrew&#93; or &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am&#44; dear Sir&#44; very resp&#39;y yours<lb/>
            B. Felsenthal<lb/></p>
        </body>
